arch:property.oc:show_val: East of the step (Locus 16) in the Shrine Room North Corridor.

Phase IV: Nabataean Grand Design: 1st c. BCE to CE 1st c. The remainder of the subterranean canalization is installed including the East Plaza Great Cistern. The East and South Perimeter Walls are installed and Rooms A and B and the Tabun Cave Room are built into the casemate of the East Perimeter Wall. The East Plaza and South Passageway are paved and the temple Forecourt is raised and laid with a small hexagonal pavement. Residential Quarter is built in the southwest corner of the precinct. Also at this time the Central Staircase of Phase II is blocked and the lateral East and West Staircases are constructed to access the Lower Temenos.

Locus 17 is the floor pavement of the northwest corner of the Shrine Room comprised of one roughly hewn rectangular sandstone and two small snecking stones. Two rows of stones are extant and on the whole the subfloor is well-preserved. No hexagonal paving stones are present. It is unclear how this corner of the Shrine Room connects to the room’s interior as the rest of the area is concealed under the east west extension of the late West Walkway Wall. Locus 17 has been assigned to this stage because of its location within the Shrine Room, previously assigned to the tetrastyle expansion of the Great Temple.
0.50 m north south-by-0.33 m east west (exposed).
